post_text:
Beginning August 17, we will provide daily drive-thru meal service from 7 school sites across the district. Meals will be distributed 5 days per week from 7-8:30 AM. This change in time will allow parents to pick up meals for that day and return home before students log on for distance learning instruction. This time change may also be more convenient for working parents. Students do not need to be present in the car to pick up school meals.
Visit Food Services Meal Distribution website page for more information! https://bit.ly/31K21Gp #svusdshines

Principal Foulk is thrilled to be the new Principal of Trabuco Hills High School and looks forward to the opportunity to be a part of the Mustang team as they continue to develop innovative ideas to affect student achievement and prepare students for the challenges of the 21st century.

Congratulations Principal Foulk and WELCOME to SVUSD Family!

post_text: Update #18: SVUSD will extend the closure of our school facilities and students will not return in-person to our campuses for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. I would like to emphasize that this does not mean the 2019-2020 academic year has ended. While we will continue to stay physically apart, the expectation is that our teachers will continue to provide instruction and our students will stay engaged in their learning until the very last day of school on June 11, 2020. Distance learning and SVUSD services will continue, including school counseling services, mental wellness supports, grab-and-go meals, Chromebooks and connectivity, and more. Grab and Go meals will continue to be served during Spring Recess on Monday and Thursday, as well as through the remainder of the school year.

Estimadas familias de SVUSD:
A la luz de la Orden Ejecutiva de quedarse en casa que dio el Gobernador Newsom esta noche (19 de marzo), el SVUSD observará el cierre de los edificios en todo el distrito mañana, 20 de marzo, para determinar los próximos pasos inmediatos. El servicio de almuerzo se brindará entre las 12:00 y la 1:00 pm únicamente en el Centro de Nutrición SVUSD ubicado en Peter A. Hartman Way el viernes 20 de marzo. Entendemos que algunas familias esperaban recoger materiales y/o Chromebooks mañana, pero a la luz de los eventos recientes, los administradores de su escuela se comunicarán con usted sobre cómo funcionará el proceso de recolección en los próximos días.

Si necesita asistencia técnica para los Chromebooks, envíe un correo electrónico a portalsupport@svusd.org. El centro de asistencia telefónica de la mesa de ayuda estará cerrado el 20 de marzo.

Entendemos que puede haber preguntas con respecto a los próximos días y enviaremos una actualización a todas las familias y al personal mañana, 20 de marzo.

post_text:
Dear SVUSD Families,
In light of tonight’s (March 19th) Stay Home Executive Order from Governor Newsom, SVUSD will be observing a district-wide facilities closure tomorrow, March 20th, in order to determine immediate next steps. Lunch service will be provided between 12:00 and 1:00 pm solely at the SVUSD Nutrition Center located on Peter A. Hartman Way on Friday, March 20th. We understand that some families were expecting to pick up materials and/or Chromebooks tomorrow, but in light of recent events, your school administrator(s) will be communicating with you on how the pickup process will function in the upcoming days.

If you require technical support for Chromebooks please email portalsupport@svusd.org. The phone help desk support center will be closed on March 20th.

We understand that there may be questions regarding the next few days and we will send an update to all families and staff tomorrow, March 20th.

post_text: Update #9 March 13, 2020 (3:45 pm) : In light of the recent National Emergency declaration by President Trump, along with the input of several county and district officials, the SVUSD Board of Education, in an emergency session decided that all Saddleback Valley Unified schools will be closed beginning Monday, March 16th through Friday, March 27th, with the possibility of closing for a third week as the situation warrants. At this time, Spring Break will remain during the week of April 6. This decision has not been made lightly, as we are aware of the far-reaching impact school closures will have on our families, staff, and community. There are no confirmed cases of coronavirus among SVUSD students or staff and the closure is a proactive measure that is being taken to help prevent the spread of the virus and to protect public health. Thank you for your partnership and support as we ensure the continued safety of our students and staff. Dr. Turner’s letter available at http://conta.cc/38QwmVs

These teachers are part of the Intensive Reading PLC. Intensive Reading is a reading intervention course offered to English Learners (ELs) at all secondary sites. It is a course designed to support ELs in their literacy skills.

Utilizing the READ180 Universal program, the course consists of a blended learning model that include software sessions adapted to students’ individual reading inventory data, independent reading, and small group instruction.

The Intensive Reading PLC will continue its work this school year, with plans to refine assessment for learning practices. In addition to its collaboration process focused on student outcomes, Intensive Reading teachers work very closely with Services for English Learners staff for individual coaching and classroom-embedded professional development to support their individual growth as teachers.

#SVInnovates #SVUSDShines #EnglishLearners
text:
These teachers are part of the Intensive Reading PLC. Intensive Reading is a reading intervention course offered to English Learners (ELs) at all secondary sites. It is a course designed to support ELs in their literacy skills.

Utilizing the READ180 Universal program, the course consists of a blended learning model that include software sessions adapted to students’ individual reading inventory data, independent reading, and small group instruction.

The Intensive Reading PLC will continue its work this school year, with plans to refine assessment for learning practices. In addition to its collaboration process focused on student outcomes, Intensive Reading teachers work very closely with Services for English Learners staff for individual coaching and classroom-embedded professional development to support their individual growth as teachers.

#SVInnovates #SVUSDShines #EnglishLearners

Time for another #TBT (Throwback Thursday)!

This time let's take a trip back to the 1987-1988 school year. A Los Alisos student was photographed for the yearbook on what was then considered a pretty high tech personal computer- an Apple lle.

When brand new, the Apple lle would of cost $1,395, which is equal to approximately $3500 in today's US dollar. It came equipped with a whopping 64k of RAM (almost 1MB!), and the ability to utilize the TAB and Delete button for the first time!

Definitely does not look like the technology our students use today. We hope you enjoyed this trip down memory lane!

post_text:
Congratulation to Laguna Hills High Alumnus Shane Bieber! He won last night's MLB All-Star Game MVP.

From the Orange County Register:

“I didn’t really know what to think,” Bieber, 24, said of getting the news he’d won the award. “I kind of lost all feeling in my body. It’s an incredible feeling now that it’s kind of sinking in. Being able to do it in front of the home crowd in my first All-Star Game is definitely something that I didn’t expect.”

Bieber, who was a late addition to the All-Star roster last week, is the third player to win the All-Star Game MVP in his home ballpark.

The crowd chanted “Let’s Go Bieber,” during his performance.

“I heard everything and really soaked it all in,” Bieber said. “I can’t thank the fans enough for making that moment for me.”

Let's go, Bieber! ⚾️

She is now the national spokesperson of the Jessie Rees Foundation, a motivational speaker, coach, sports commentator, emcee, and host for world-class sporting events.

Congratulations to Trabuco Hills High School's Kyliegh Wilkerson! She won the Outstanding Competitor award at last night's Orange County Register Athletes of the Year banquet.

A big congratulations to La Paz Intermediate Instrumental Music Teacher Dan Robbins on being a quarterfinalist in the Recording Academy and Grammy Museum 2020 Music Educator Award! Only 189 teachers have made it to the quarterfinalist round out of 3,300 initial nominations.

The Music Educator Award was established to recognize current educators (kindergarten through college, public and private schools) who have made a significant and lasting contribution to the field of music education and who demonstrate a commitment to the broader cause of maintaining music education in the schools.

The semifinalists will be announced in September. For more information, please visit www.grammymusicteacher.com.

Kids For Wish Kids OCIE
March 16, 2017 at 5:00 PM ·

As a student board member of Saddleback Valley Unified School District , Jackson launched a district-wide coin drive last month, working with over 25 schools to collect coins for Make-A-Wish! After only one week, Jackson dropped off over $15,000 in coins - the largest donation generated by a student under 18 in years! We are humbled to work with this young man, who is making such a huge difference this year!
